 and War in Thucydides -- tInquiring about Humans and Nature: Creativity, Planning, and Serendipity -- tThe Liberal Arts Core: Engaging with Current Events, 2016–2020 -- tCrossings: Teaching “Roots and Routes: Reading/Writing Identity, Migration, and Culture” -- tThe Architecture of a Black Feminist Classroom: Pedagogical Praxis in “Where #BlackLivesMatter Meets #MeToo” -- tTruth-Telling in History and Literature: Constructive Uncertainty -- tCovid Core Lessons -- tAcknowledgments -- tAppendix A: The Vision Animating the Boston College Core Curriculum -- tAppendix B: Boston College Core Curriculum Required Courses -- tAppendix C: Complex Problem and Enduring Question Courses, 2015–2021 -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book tells the story of how a team of colleagues at Boston College took an unusual approach (working with a design consultancy) to renewing their core and in the process energized administrators, faculty, and students to view liberal arts education as an ongoing process of innovation. It aims to provide insight into what they did and why they did it and to provide a candid account of what has worked and what has not worked. Although all institutions are different, they believe their experiences can provide guidance to others who want to change their general education curriculum or who are being asked to teach core or general education courses in new ways.The book also includes short essays by a number of faculty colleagues who have been teaching in BC’s new innovative core courses, providing practical advice about the challenges of trying interdisciplinary teaching, team teaching, project-or problem-based learning, intentional reflection, and other new structures and pedagogies for the first time. It will also address some of the nuts and bolts issues they have encountered when trying to create structures to make curriculum change sustainable over time and to foster ongoing innovation.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCurriculum changezMassachusetts. 0aEducation, HigherzMassachusettszBoston Metropolitan Area. 0aEducation, HumanisticxCurriculazMassachusetts. 0aEducational innovationszMassachusetts. 4aCatholic Studies. 4aEducation. 4aSociology. 7aEDUCATION / Curricula.2bisacsh  aActive Learning.  aCore Curriculum.  aCurriculum Revision.  aGeneral Education.  aHuman-Centered Design.  aInnovation.  aInterdisciplinary.  aJesuit Education.  aLiberal Arts.  aTeam Teaching.1 aAdair, Allison, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnderson, Lynne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Robert C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartlett, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBole, William, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBottorf, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Andy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBoynton, Andy, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aButler, Jack, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aButler, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallahan, Daniel M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCallahan, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Mary Thomas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Mary Thomas, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aEisenfeld, Hanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/